      "uiTag": "Misconception check",
      "uiColor": "red",
      "title": "Quick question first…",
      "question": "A light bulb is 20% efficient. What happens to the other 80% of the energy?",
      "options": [
        "It is destroyed",
        "It is stored inside the bulb",
        "It is transferred to thermal energy stores (wasted as heat)",
        "It goes back to the power supply"
      ],
      "correctIndex": 2,
      "misconceptionFeedback": "⚠️ Common misconception! Energy is never destroyed. The 80% is not 'lost' - it is transferred to thermal energy stores of the bulb and surroundings. It is 'wasted' because it’s not useful light, but it still exists as thermal energy.",
      "correctFeedback": "✓ Correct! The 80% is dissipated to thermal energy stores of the surroundings. It’s wasted because we wanted light, not heat. Energy is always conserved: the 'waste' energy still exists.",
      "bestSource": "BEST resource: AQA GCSE Physics specification 4.1.3: Energy and efficiency"
    },
    {
      "id": "concept",
      "type": "concept",
      "uiTag": "Concept",
      "uiColor": "blue",
      "title": "Efficiency",
      "bodyHTML": "<strong>Efficiency</strong> is the proportion of input energy that is transferred to <strong>useful</strong> output energy stores. No device is 100% efficient, so some energy is always <strong>dissipated</strong> (wasted) to thermal energy stores of the surroundings. Efficiency can be expressed as a <strong>decimal</strong> (0 to 1) or a <strong>percentage</strong> (0% to 100%).",
      "keyEquation": "efficiency = useful output energy ÷ total input energy",
      "diagram": {
        "type": "equation-breakdown",
        "variables": [
          {
            "symbol": "η",
            "label": "Efficiency",
            "unit": "decimal or %",
            "color": "cyan"
          },
          {
            "symbol": "Eout",
            "label": "Useful output energy",
            "unit": "J",
            "color": "purple"
          },
          {
            "symbol": "Ein",
            "label": "Total input energy",
            "unit": "J",
            "color": "amber"
          }
        ],
        "relationships": [
          "Efficiency is always less than 1 (or 100%)",
          "Multiply decimal by 100 to get percentage",
          "Can also use power: efficiency = useful power out ÷ total power in"
        ]
      },
      "keyWords": [
        "efficiency",
        "useful energy",
        "wasted energy",
        "dissipated",
        "thermal energy",
        "percentage",
        "decimal"
      ],
      "commonErrors": [
        "Forgetting to multiply by 100 when the answer should be a percentage",
        "Dividing total input by useful output (the fraction is upside down)",
        "Giving an efficiency greater than 100% (impossible!)"
      ],
      "keyEquationTex": "\\eta = \\frac{E_{\\text{out}}}{E_{\\text{in}}}"
